d\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[XL Recordings]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Sweden<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cdon.se/musik/m-i-a-/kala-749752 |title=Kala \u2013 Album \u2013 M.i.a. |language=Swedish |publisher=CDON.se |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B000T7QX78 |title=Kala |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hmv.ca/Products/Detail/146890.aspx |title=Kala by M I A |publisher=HMV Canada |accessdate=30 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304171321/https://www.hmv.ca/products/detail/146890.aspx |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|21 August 2007\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|France<ref>{{cite web |url=http://musique.fnac.com/a2007062/M-I-A-Kala-CD-album |title=Kala \u2013 M.I.A |language=French |publisher=[[Fnac]] |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interscope.com/artist/releases/detail.aspx?pid=341&aid=555 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122225921/http://interscope.com/artist/releases/detail.aspx?pid=341&aid=555 |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 January 2009 |title=M.I.A. : Releases : Kala |publisher=[[Interscope Records]] |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|{{flatlist|\n* XL Recordings\n* [[Interscope Records]]}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Germany<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indigo.de/unser_programm/titel/90553/ |title=M.I.A.: Kala |language=German |publisher=Indigo |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|24 August 2007\n|rowspan=\"4\"|XL Recordings\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B001GCWRKM |title=Kala (2008) |publisher=Amazon.co.uk |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|13 October 2008\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Expanded\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|France<ref>{{cite web |url=http://musique.fnac.com/a2501230/M-I-A-Kala-Expanded-version-CD-album |title=Kala \u2013 Expanded version \u2013 M.I.A |language=French |publisher=Fnac |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref>\n|14 October 2008\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanity.com.au/products/2117641/Kala_Expanded |title=Kala (Expanded) |publisher=[[Sanity (music store)|Sanity]] |accessdate=30 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203001244/http://www.sanity.com.au/products/2117641/Kala_Expanded |archive-date=3 February 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|25 October 2008\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|type=album|name=Kala|80900}}\n\n{{M.I.A.}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kala (Album)}}\n[[Category:2007 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Diplo]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by M.I.A. (rapper)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Switch]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Timbaland]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records albums]]\n[[Category:Interscope Geffen A&M Records albums]]\n[[Category:M.I.A. (rapper) albums]]\n[[Category:XL Recordings albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name = Kala\n| type = studio\n| artist = [[M.I.A. (rapper)|M.I.A.]]\n| cover = M.I.A. - Kala.png\n| alt = The head and shoulders of a woman wearing sunglasses and a fur hat, enclosed in a circle around which the words \"Fight On!\" are repeatedly written. Surrounding this are four smaller versions of the same image in negative, various brightly coloured geometric shapes, and the words MIA and KALA in capital letters\n| released = {{Start date|df=yes|2007|8|8}}\n| recorded = 2006\u201307\n| studio =\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Electronic dance music|Dance]]|[[world music|world]]|[[hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| length = 47:32\n| label = {{hlist|[[XL Recordings|XL]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| producer = {{hlist|[[Blaqstarr]]|[[Diplo]]|M.I.A.|[[Morganics]]|[[Switch (house DJ)|Switch]]|[[Timbaland]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Arular]]\n| prev_year = 2005\n| next_title = [[Maya (M.I.A. album)|Maya]]\n| next_year = 2010\n| misc = {{Singles\n | name = Kala\n | type = studio\n | single1 = [[Bird Flu (song)|Bird Flu]]\n | single1date = 23 November 2006\n | single2 = [[Boyz (song)|Boyz]]\n | single2date = 11 June 2007\n | single3 = [[Jimmy (song)|Jimmy]]\n | single3date = 1 October 2007\n | single4 = [[Paper Planes (M.I.A. song)|Paper Planes]]\n | single4date = 11 February 2008\n}}\n}}\n'''''Kala''''' is the second studio album by the English rapper, songwriter, and producer [[M.I.A. (rapper)|M.I.A.]]. It was released on 8&nbsp;August 2007 by [[XL Recordings]]. M.I.A. named the album after her mother, in contrast to her first album ''[[Arular]]'', which was named after her father, and said her mother's struggles in life are a major theme of the recording. She began recording the album in early 2006 and worked on the tracks in various locations around the world. \n\nM.I.A.'s debut album ''[[Arular]]'' was released in 2005 and achieved critical acclaim. Plans for the second album, ''Kala'', were first revealed when she spoke later that year of her intention to work with American producer [[Timbaland]], who was anticipated to produce the bulk of the album. However, she was unable to gain a long-term work [[Visa (document)|visa]] to enter the US, reportedly due to her family's connections with [[guerrillas]] in [[Sri Lanka]]. M.I.A. instead opted to record the album at a variety of locations around the world, including [[India]], [[Trinidad]], [[Liberia]], [[Jamaica]] and [[Australia]]. \n\nThe album features musical styles including [[dance music]] and makes extensive use of [[South Asia|South Asian]] music such as that of the [[urumi (drum)|urumee]], a drum used in [[gaana]] music native to [[Tamil Nadu]], India. It was mainly written and produced by M.I.A. and [[Switch (house DJ)|Switch]], and features contributions from Timbaland, [[Diplo]], [[Afrikan Boy]] and [[The Wilcannia Mob]]. M.I.A. and Switch relied heavily on [[Logic Pro]], a [[digital audio workstation]] produced by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], and were able to capture vocals and background sounds outside the traditional studio environment, using a microphone and a [[Macbook|Macbook Pro.]] \n\n''Kala'' charted in 14 countries and topped the [[Dance/Electronic Albums|''Billboard'' Top Electronic Albums]] chart. It spawned the singles \"[[Bird Flu (song)|Bird Flu]]\", \"[[Boyz (song)|Boyz]]\", \"[[Jimmy (song)|Jimmy]]\" and the global hit single \"[[Paper Planes (M.I.A. song)|Paper Planes]]\". By 2013, the album was certified [[RIAA certification|Gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for sales of at least 500,000 copies in the US, and [[Music Canada#Certification awards|Platinum]] in Canada. It received widespread critical acclaim and was ranked as one of the best albums of 2007 by many publications. Since its initial release, it has often been cited among the best albums of the 21st century by critics, and has been ranked by several publications as one of the greatest albums of all time.\n\n== Composition and recording ==\n[[File:Switchdj.jpg|left|150px|thumb|Dave \"[[Switch (house DJ)|Switch]]\" Taylor, who co-wrote and co-produced ''Kala'']]\nM.I.A. (Mathangi \"Maya\" Arulpragasam) had released her debut album ''[[Arular]]'' in 2005, which achieved critical acclaim and sold 130,000 copies.<ref name=\"via\" /> Plans for a second album were first revealed when she spoke later that year of her intention to work with American producer [[Timbaland]]. At one point it was anticipated that he would produce the bulk of the album.<ref name=\"CC\" /><ref name=\"modemand\">{{cite video|people=Leah Miller (Presenter), M.I.A. (Interviewee) |title=MuchMusic Much on Demand: M.I.A. Transcript|date=September 2005 |url=http://www.muchmusic.com/music/artists/transcripts.asp?artist=1213 |publisher=[[MuchMusic]], [[CTVglobemedia]]|work=[[Much on Demand]]  |medium=TV-Series |location=[[Toronto]] |accessdate=24 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013163743/http://www.muchmusic.com/music/artists/transcripts.asp?artist=1213 |archivedate=13 October 2007 }}</ref> However, she was unable to gain a long-term work [[Visa (document)|visa]] to enter the US, reportedly due to her family's connections with guerrillas in [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\"via\">{{cite web |url=http://www.today.com/id/20379484 |title=M.I.A. doesn't need a visa, just inspiration |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |publisher=[[NBCNews.com]] |date=21 August 2007 |accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref> This led to conflicts between the two artists' schedules and meant that Timbaland's involvement was restricted to a poorly received guest verse on the track \"Come Around\".<ref name=\"CC\">{{cite web|url=http://thephoenix.com/Boston/Music/46609-Culture-clash/?page=2 |title=Culture clash |first=Nick |last=Sylvester |accessdate=15 September 2009 |date=5 September 2007 |work=[[The Phoenix (newspaper)|The Boston Phoenix]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014015146/http://thephoenix.com/Boston/Music/46609-Culture-clash/?page=2 |archivedate=14 October 2012}}</ref> M.I.A. instead opted to record the album at a variety of locations around the world,<ref name=\"via\" /> beginning by travelling to India following the last date of her [[Arular Tour]] in Japan in February 2006.<ref name=\"urb\" />\n\n{{listen\n|pos=right\n | filename = Bird Flu - MIA.ogg\n | title = M.I.A. \"Bird Flu\" (2007)\n | description = Short clip of \"Bird Flu\" showing the track's use of [[urumi (drum)|urumee]] drums.\n | format = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nShe initially travelled to India to meet [[A. R. Rahman]], but found it hard to communicate her ideas to him and the planned musical collaboration did not take place.<ref name=\"miafadermag07\"/> Rahman did, however, provide M.I.A. with a number of contacts and allow her to use his studio, where 22 members of drumming group The Tapes were recorded for ''Kala''.<ref name=\"logic\">{{ cite web | url=https://www.apple.com/logicstudio/in-action/switch/?sr=hotnews | title=Dave \"Switch\" Taylor: Producing M.I.A. | first=Joe|last=Cellini | publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] | accessdate=18 December 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"tapes\">{{ cite web | url=http://emusician.com/remixmag/artists_interviews/musicians/mia_switch_diplo_kala/ | title=Out on a whim \u2013 M.I.A., aka Maya Arulpragasam, Switch and Diplo on recording Kala | last=Moayeri | first=Lily | work=Remix | accessdate=19 December 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824175941/http://emusician.com/remixmag/artists_interviews/musicians/mia_switch_diplo_kala/ | archivedate=24 August 2010}}</ref> Producer [[Switch (house DJ)|Switch]], who had initially travelled to India purely to engineer the planned sessions, ultimately became involved in the composition of several tracks for the album.<ref name=\"miafadermag07\" /> A visit to [[Angola]] to work with DJ Znobia was cancelled after Znobia was involved in a car accident,<ref name=\"miafadermag07\" /> but M.I.A. was able to record in [[Trinidad]], [[Liberia]], [[Jamaica]] and Australia.<ref name=\"rollingstone\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spin-cdnsrc.texterity.com/spin/200812/?pg=65|title=M.I.A.: POW!|first=Lorraine|last=Ali|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=15 September 2009|date=December 2008}}</ref> She and Switch relied heavily on [[Logic Pro]], a [[digital audio workstation]] produced by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], and were able to capture vocals and background sounds outside the traditional studio environment, using a microphone and a [[Macbook|Macbook Pro.]]<ref name=\"logic\"/><ref name=\"tapes\"/> The album features guest vocals from [[Afrikan Boy]], [[The Wilcannia Mob]], and Timbaland, and further collaborations with Switch, [[Blaqstarr]], [[Morganics]] and [[Diplo]].<ref name=\"Kellman\"/> She likened the process of recording the album to \"making a big old [[marble cake]] with lots of different countries and influences. Then you slice it up and call each slice a song\".<ref name=\"miafadermag07\">{{cite web |last=Wagner |first=Alex |url=http://www.thefader.com/2007/08/07/video-interview-mia-jimmy/ |title=Life in Exile |work=[[The Fader]] |date=8 July 2007 |accessdate=29 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n''Kala'' is named after M.I.A.'s mother, in contrast to her previous album, ''[[Arular]]'', which was named after her father.<ref>{{cite magazine | title=M.I.A. : Kala| url= http://drownedinsound.com/releases/11132/reviews/2310992- | magazine= [[Drowned in Sound]] | accessdate=15 September 2009|date=23 December 2007|first=Sam|last=Lewis}}</ref> She contends that ''Arular'' was a \"masculine\" album, but that ''Kala'' \"is about my mum and her struggle\u2013how do you work, feed your children, nurture them and give them the power of information?\"<ref name=\"urb\">{{cite news | last=Hawkins|first=Si|title= M.I.A.: World Party| url= http://www.urb.com/features/183/MIAWorldParty.php?PageId=2 | work = [[URB (magazine)|URB]] | date=17 May 2006|accessdate=24 May 2007 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20071013164618/http://www.urb.com/features/183/MIAWorldParty.php?PageId=2 |archivedate = 13 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"miapw\">{{cite news|title=What's Up With M.I.A. |url=http://philadelphiaweekly.com/view.php?id=12933 |work=[[Philadelphia Weekly]] |date=6 September 2006 |accessdate=14 September 2009 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20071013165645/http://philadelphiaweekly.com/view.php?id=12933 |archivedate=13 October 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> She further summed the album up as \"shapes, colours, Africa, street, power, bitch, nu world, and brave.\"<ref>{{cite news | last=Empire|first=Kitty| title= 10 essential albums for Spring| url= https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2007/mar/11/featuresreview.review | work=[[The Observer]]|date=11 March 2007 |accessdate=7 April 2007}}</ref> According to Dominic Horner of ''[[The Independent]]'', the album's music may not be appropriately described exclusively as either [[electronic dance music|dance]] or [[world music]], but it is a mixture of the two.<ref>{{cite news|last=Horner|first=Dominic|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/magazines/music-reviews-mia-athlete-super-furry-animals-398003.html|title=Music reviews: M.I.A; Athlete; Super Furry Animals|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|location=London|date=26 October 2007|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> Music critic [[Robert Christgau]] characterised its music as an \"eclectic world-underclass dance amalgam\",<ref name=\"rollingstone\"/> and Jonathan Brown of the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' cited ''Kala'' as a proper introduction to \"[[world fusion]]\", a genre that \"blends sounds from across the globe which wouldn't \u2013 and some say shouldn't \u2013 be put together.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Jonathan|date=6 September 2007|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/everything-you-ever-wanted-to-know-about-pop-but-were-too-old-to-ask-26316114.html|title=Everything you ever wanted to know about pop (but were too old to ask)|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> By contrast, [[NPR]]'s Oliver Wang argued that, rather than a \"so-called world music fusion\" attempt, ''Kala'' is \"agitated, propulsive pop\" informed by international sounds.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wang|first=Oliver|date=21 August 2007|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=13831187|title=M.I.A.: Back in Action with 'Kala'|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> Music journalist [[Jody Rosen]] called it \"an [[agitprop]] dance record\" that reappropriates [[hip hop music|hip hop]] in an international setting with beatbox [[riddim]]s, \"playground\" rhymes, unconventional samples, and gunshot sounds.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rosen|first=Jody|authorlink=Jody Rosen|date=19 March 2013|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/how-m-i-a-made-kala-20130319|title=How M.I.A. Made 'Kala'|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:AfrikanBoyMIA.jpg|thumb|right|240px|alt=A man wearing an African-style hat, sunglasses, and a large gold chain, and holding a microphone. In the background a woman in brightly coloured clothing and sunglasses is also holding a microphone and is waving one hand in the air|[[Afrikan Boy]] performing live with M.I.A. in France. He provided vocals for the track \"Hussel\".]]\nThe tracks \"[[Boyz (song)|Boyz]]\" and \"[[Bird Flu (song)|Bird Flu]]\" use [[urumi (drum)|urumee]] drums, a signature instrument of [[Gaana]], a [[Music of Tamil Nadu|Tamil]] genre of music, with which M.I.A. was familiar from her time spent living in Sri Lanka. She later worked on these tracks in Trinidad, where she absorbed influences from the country's love of [[soca music]].<ref name=\"miafadermag07\"/><ref name=\"villagevoicemia\"/><ref name=\"miaexclaimkala07\"/> The lyrics of \"Boyz\" deal with the artist's time in Jamaica, and reference Jamaican dance moves.<ref name=\"miafadermag07\"/> The song \"Hussel\" began as an image in M.I.A.'s head of [[refugees]] being smuggled in boats, which she expressed musically by imagining how \"if they banged that beat on the side of a boat, what would it sound like? That's why it's all [[echo (phenomenon)|echo-y]] and [[submarine|submarine-y]]\". The sounds on the intro were recorded from [[Kerala]]n [sic] fishermen chanting as they pull their fishing boats into the water.<ref name=\"miafadermag07\"/> \"World Town\" used instrumentation from the temple music she recalled waking up to as a child in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"miafadermag07\"/> After playing the track to children in Liberia, she expressed a desire to record a video for the song there.<ref name=\"miafadermag07\"/> M.I.A.'s \"flat, unaffected vocals and delivery of lyrics\" on some songs drew comparisons to British [[post-punk]] bands such as [[Delta 5]] and [[The Slits]]. She says it \"was just what was happening to me naturally&nbsp;... I wanted it to be difficult and raw and not get into it so much\".<ref name=\"villagevoicemia\"/>\n\n[[Afrikan Boy]], an exponent of [[grime (music)|grime]], a UK-based genre of [[urban music]], provided vocals on the song \"Hussel\". M.I.A. opted to work with him because she felt that he seemed comfortable with his identity as a \"real immigrant\" and because his background was different to that of most [[Master of Ceremonies#Hip hop culture|MCs]] in the genre.<ref name=\"miaexclaimkala07\"/> She had originally planned to include \"Mango Pickle Down River\"\u2014her remix of [[The Wilcannia Mob]]'s song \"Down River\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/11/29/1038386308756.html|title=The Wilcannia mob|date=29 November 2002|work=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref>\u2014on a [[mixtape]], but chose to include it on the album because she felt it was rare to hear the \"[[Aboriginal music|aboriginal voice]]\" in recorded music,<ref name=\"miaexclaimkala07\"/> and described opening track \"Bamboo Banga\" as having a \"bamboo-stick beat, [[house (music)|house-y]] feel\".<ref name=\"miaexclaimkala07\">{{cite web |last=Lindsay |first=Cam |url=http://exclaim.ca/Interviews/WebExclusive/mia |title=M.I.A. |work=[[Exclaim!]] |date=September 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2008}}</ref> The song \"[[Jimmy (song)|Jimmy]]\" was included as a tribute to her mother and is M.I.A.'s version of an old [[Bollywood]] film track to which she used to dance at parties as a child.<ref name=\"villagevoicemia\">{{cite news|last=Breihan |first=Tom |title=Status Ain't Hood interviews M.I.A. |url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2007/07/status_aint_hoo_28.php |work=[[The Village Voice]] |accessdate=6 March 2008 |date=18 July 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915191143/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2007/07/status_aint_hoo_28.php |archivedate=15 September 2008}}</ref> Despite the involvement of [[Baltimore club]] musician Blaqstarr, \"The Turn\" turned out to be the album's only ballad, and the track has been described as the least like [[club music]].<ref name=\"miaexclaimkala07\"/> \"20 Dollar\" was written about the relative ease of buying [[AK-47]]s in war-torn [[Liberia]].<ref>{{cite web | title= Track by Track : M.I.A.| publisher=[[VH1]]|first=Jonathan|last=Durbin|url= http://www.vh1.com/artists/interview/1567706/20070823/mia__4_.jhtml | date=23 August 2007 | accessdate=23 December 2008}}</ref> \"XR2\" recalls part of the artist's life growing up with [[rave music]] in early 1990s London,<ref name=\"miaexclaimkala07\"/> while the song \"[[Paper Planes (M.I.A. song)|Paper Planes]]\" jokingly plays on M.I.A.'s problems with visas and certain perceptions of immigrants.<ref>{{cite web | title= M.I.A. Strike, Match, Light, Fire| publisher=MTV|url= http://www.mtv.com/overdrive/?id=1574938&vid=190780 | date=3 December 2007 | accessdate=6 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Release and artwork ==\nIn April 2007 ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' reported that ''Kala'' would be released on 26 June of that year.<ref name=\"mia03\">{{cite web | first=Adrian|last=Covert|title=M.I.A. sets release date for upcoming album 'Kala' | url= http://www.prefixmag.com/news/mia-kala-release/9987/ | publisher = Prefix | date=10 April 2007|accessdate=10 December 2008}}</ref> After being delayed for unknown reasons, the album was eventually released by [[XL Recordings]] on 8&nbsp;August 2007 in Japan and on 20 August in the UK, and by [[Interscope Records]] on 21 August in the United States.<ref name=\"grid\">{{cite web|url=http://www.miauk.com/info/?m=200705|title=Tour Dates and News|publisher=M.I.A.|accessdate=11 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809112524/http://www.miauk.com/info/?m=200705 |archivedate=9 August 2007}}</ref> The Japanese edition featured three extra tracks not included on the versions released in other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beggarsjapan.com/artists/MIA/WPCB-10029/index.html|title=Kala|publisher=Beggars Group Japan|accessdate=15 December 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120202416/http://www.beggarsjapan.com/artists/MIA/WPCB-10029/index.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=20 November 2008}}</ref> Following the unexpected commercial success of \"Paper Planes\", ''Kala'' was re-issued in the United Kingdom in October 2008.<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.nme.com/news/mia/39504| title=MIA announces 'Paper Planes' UK release | work=[[NME]]|date=4 September 2008 | accessdate=4 February 2009}}</ref> A 4&nbsp;November 2008 US re-release was announced,<ref name=\"reissue\">{{ cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23399805/mias_unexpected_smash |title=M.I.A.'s unexpected smash |first=Brian |last=Hiatt |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=16 October 2008 |accessdate=10 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216032838/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/23399805/mias_unexpected_smash |archivedate=16 February 2009}}</ref> but as of late 2009 the album had not been re-issued in the United States.\n\nThe album's packaging includes photographs taken by M.I.A. and others in [[Liberia]] and [[Jamaica]].<ref name=\"notes\"/> The cover artwork to ''Kala'', designed by Steve Loveridge, features neon [[fractal]] patterns and repeated slogans, including \"Fight On! Fight On! Fight On!\", which surrounds her image on the front cover.<ref name=\"mia02\">{{cite web | first=Dan|last=Nishimoto|title= M.I.A. : Kala| url= http://www.prefixmag.com/reviews/mia/kala/16147/ | publisher = Prefix | date=21 August 2007| accessdate=10 December 2008}}</ref> The cover was considered garish, prompting ''[[The Village Voice]]'' to comment \"Maybe one day [she'll] make an album cover that it doesn't hurt to look at\".<ref name=\"villagevoicemia\" /> Additional graphics for the album were provided by English fashion designer [[Carri Mundane]] (also known as Cassette Playa) and Steve Loveridge.<ref name=\"notes\"/> The album's artwork was inspired by [[African art]], \"from dictator fashion to old stickers on the back of cars,\" which M.I.A hoped, like her artwork extended \"Okley Run\" clothing range, would capture \"a 3-D sense, the shapes, the prints, the sound, film, technology, politics, economics\" of a certain time.<ref>{{cite web | first=|last=|title= MIA Talks Fashion| url= http://www.thefader.com/2008/10/24/stylee-fridays-mia-talks-fashion/ | work = [[The Fader]] | date=24 October 2008| accessdate=24 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Promotion ==\n[[File:M.i.a.148.jpg|thumb|right|upright|alt=A dark-skinned woman wearing a black hat and black clothing holding a microphone while performing on stage to a crowd of people. The performance is taking place outdoors and part of a rollercoaster is visible in the background.|M.I.A. performing at the [[Siren Music Festival]] during her tour in support of the album]]\nM.I.A. began her promotion of the new album with a live appearance at [[Radio 1's Big Weekend]] in [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]] in May 2007, where she performed six songs from ''Kala''.<ref>{{cite web | title=Radio 1's Big Weekend : M.I.A.| url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/bigweekend/2007/artists/mia/ | publisher = [[BBC]] | accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> In July she began the full [[KALA Tour]] with dates in the United States before going on to play a number of [[Music festival|festivals]] in Europe and America.<ref>{{cite web|title=A globalist rapper pauses for breath |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20071005a1.html |work=[[The Japan Times]] |first=Daniel |last=Robson |date=5 October 2007 |accessdate=19 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080329094356/http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20071005a1.html |archivedate=29 March 2008}}</ref> After dates in Asia,<ref>{{cite web | title= M.I.A. adds U.S. dates to Summer Tour| url= http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/43913-mia-adds-us-dates-to-summer-tour | work = [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] | date=28 June 2007 | accessdate=14 September 2009 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080307071803/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/43913-mia-adds-us-dates-to-summer-tour |archivedate = 7 March 2008}}</ref> she returned to America for a series of shows in October and November,<ref name=\"miatour07\">{{cite web | title= M.I.A. adds shows with The Cool Kids| url= http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/46027-mia-adds-shows-with-the-cool-kids | work = Pitchfork | date=1 October 2007 | accessdate=14 September 2009 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080307034000/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/46027-mia-adds-shows-with-the-cool-kids |archivedate = 7 March 2008}}</ref> before ending the year with concerts in the UK.<ref>{{cite web | title= MIA announces new UK tour| url= http://www.nme.com/news/mia/31882| work = [[NME]] | date=18 October 2007 | accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> The tour continued during the first half of 2008 under the banner of the [[People Vs. Money Tour]] with further dates in North America,<ref name=\"grid\" /> although the planned European leg of the tour was eventually cancelled.<ref>{{cite magazine | title=M.I.A. cancels UK and European dates to garden| url= http://www.drownedinsound.com/news/3461094 | magazine = [[Drowned in Sound]] | accessdate=19 December 2008|first=Ashraf|last=Dumile}}</ref>\n\nThe first track from the album to be made available to the public was \"Bird Flu\", which was made available as a downloadable promotional single on 13 November 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/birdflu-single/id259312194 |title=BirdFlu \u2013 Single by M.I.A. |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] UK. [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> The first official single to be lifted from the album, \"Boyz\", was released on 11 June 2007.<ref name=\"grid\" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Solarski |first=Matthew |url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/43415-mia-namez-release-date-for-boyz-singleusb-stick |title=M.I.A. Namez Release Date for \"Boyz\" Single/USB Stick |work=Pitchfork |date=6 June 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223053348/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/43415-mia-namez-release-date-for-boyz-singleusb-stick |archivedate=23 December 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref> The second single was \"Jimmy\", which was released on 1&nbsp;October 2007.<ref>{{cite web | title= New world order|url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/sep/16/urban | work = [[The Observer]]|first=Steve|last=Yates | date=16 September 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref> The EP ''[[Paper Planes - Homeland Security Remixes EP]]'', featuring various mixes of \"Paper Planes\", was released digitally on 11 February 2008 and physically three weeks later.<ref name=\"PPHSR EP\">{{cite web | url = http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/48681-dfa-adrock-remix-mias-paper-planes-on-new-ep | title =DFA, Adrock Remix M.I.A.'s \"Paper Planes\" on New EP |first=Paul|last=Thompson| work = Pitchfork | accessdate=14 September 2009|date=13 February 2008 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080306224816/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/48681-dfa-adrock-remix-mias-paper-planes-on-new-ep |archivedate = 6 March 2008}}</ref> A new physical single version was released in the UK on 13 October 2008.<ref name=\"PPRe\">{{cite web | url = http://www.nme.com/news/mia/39504 | title =MIA Announces 'Paper Planes' UK release | work = [[NME]] | accessdate=17 December 2008|date=4 September 2008 }}</ref> Also in October 2008, ''[[How Many Votes Fix Mix EP]]'' was released, containing a remix of \"Boyz\" with [[Jay-Z]] and the tracks \"Shells\" and \"Far Far\".<ref name=\"HMVFM EP\">{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/33875-mia-releases-ep-with-jay-z-version-of-boyz/ |title=M.I.A. Releases EP With Jay-Z Version of \"Boyz\" |first=Dave |last=Maher |work=Pitchfork |accessdate=17 December 2008 |date=28 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 87/100<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Kellman\"/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev2Score = B<ref>{{cite web|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|date=20 August 2007|url=https://ew.com/article/2007/08/20/kala/|title=Kala|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Petridis\"/>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Gill\"/>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref name=\"Powers\"/>\n| rev6 = ''[[MSN Music]]'' ([[Robert Christgau#Consumer Guide|Consumer Guide]])\n| rev6Score = A+<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg2007-12.php|title=Consumer Guide|first=Robert|last=Christgau|date=December 2007|accessdate=2 July 2013|work=[[MSN Music]]}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev7Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/mia/8949 |title=Mia \u2013 Kala|first=Alex|last=Miller|date=6 September 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|work=[[NME]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064241/http://www.nme.com/reviews/mia/8949|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8Score = 8.9/10<ref name=\"pitch\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10564-kala/|title=M.I.A.: Kala|first=Mark|last=Pytlik|date=21 August 2007|accessdate=16 September 2009|work=Pitchfork}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"rollingstone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/kala-20070823|title=Kala|first=Robert|last=Christgau|authorlink=Robert Christgau|accessdate=3 July 2013|date=23 August 2007|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Walters\"/>\n}}\n''Kala'' was met with widespread critical acclaim. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 87, based on 37 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/kala/mia |title=Reviews for Kala by M.I.A. |publisher=[[Metacritic]]. [[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=5 September 2007}}</ref> \n\nIn the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', [[Ann Powers]] wrote that ''Kala'' succeeded at embodying disenfranchised characters in the dissonant [[Third World]] with \"truly multi-vocal\" music whose \"every sound signified something different, driving the music's meaning into some new corner\".<ref name=\"Powers\">{{cite web|last=Powers|first=Ann|authorlink=Ann Powers|date=20 August 2007|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/aug/20/entertainment/et-mia20|title=Third World beats|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> Andy Battaglia from ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' said the music ventured far enough where it served as both a party album and a progressive aural assault,<ref name=\"Battaglia\">{{cite news|last=Battaglia|first=Andy|date=21 August 2007|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/mia-kala,7616/|title=M.I.A.: Kala|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|location=Chicago|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> while [[AllMusic]]'s Andy Kellman felt that ''Kala'' was better for intensifying ''Arular''{{'}}s qualities and \"mixing cultures with respectful irreverence\".<ref name=\"Kellman\">{{cite web |last=Kellman |first=Andy |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/kala-mw0000584505 |title=Kala \u2013 M.I.A. |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> Barry Walters of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' credited M.I.A. with evoking both the social demands and percussive sounds of the Third World, while finding the album relevant at a time when \"more Americans than ever feel like outsiders in their own country\".<ref name=\"Walters\">{{cite journal|last=Walters|first=Barry|date=September 2007|page=127|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCQFHMhVuA8C&pg=PA127#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Immigrant Songs|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|volume=23|issue=9|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> Writing for ''[[MSN Music]]'', [[Robert Christgau]] said the lyrics were \"cannier politically\" than ''Arular'', and the music was more decisive in embodying the imagination and recreation of \"an unbowed international underclass that proves how smart it is just by stating its business, which includes taking your money\".<ref name=\"Christgau\" /> He later said that he had \"pressed\" the editors of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' to let him give ''Kala'' four-and-a-half stars in his review for the magazine, wishing he \"had the foresight to fight for five\" because the album \"kept growing on me till I even dug the Timbaland remnant ['Come Around']\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|date=12 July 2010|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bn/2010-07.php|title=Illygirl Steppin Up|work=[[Barnes & Noble|The Barnes & Noble Review]]|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nJonathan Keefe from ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' was somewhat less impressed, deeming ''Kala'' less successful than ''Arular'', which he said had more immediate hooks and clever pop sensibility.<ref name=\"Keefe\">{{cite web|last=Keefe|first=Jonathan|date=20 August 2007|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/m-i-a-kala|title=M.I.A.: Kala|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' critic Mark Pytlik said because most of M.I.A.'s lyrics gave the impression they were written \"in the service of the rhythms\", her allusions sounded more \"rewarding\" than what she literally had written.<ref name=\"pitch\"/> Andy Gill of ''[[The Independent]]'' found her lyrics unclear in their message about money and social concerns, while remarking that the gun references on \"World Town\" and \"Paper Planes\" blemished \"an otherwise fine album\".<ref name=\"Gill\">{{cite news|last=Gill |first=Andy |date=17 August 2007 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-mia-461840.html |title=Album: M.I.A. |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |location=London |accessdate=3 July 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224224241/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-mia-461840.html |archivedate=24 February 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Alexis Petridis]] wrote that ''Kala'' was still a \"unique\" listen in spite of occasionally tuneless songs.<ref name=\"Petridis\">{{cite news|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|date=16 August 2007|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/aug/17/urban.electronicmusic|title=CD: MIA, Kala|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|at=Film & Music section, p. 10|accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> Writing for ''[[NME]]'', Alex Miller acknowledged that the record's music polarised opinion, claiming that some members of the magazine's staff had \"fed several copies [of the album] into the shredder claiming aural abuse\", although others went on to praise the album for its innovation and referred to it as M.I.A.'s masterpiece.<ref name=\"NMEGreatest\" />\n\n=== Rankings ===\nAt the end of 2007, ''Kala'' was named one of the year's best albums in critics' lists, including rankings at number&nbsp;eight (''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]''<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=2007 Rewind: Records of the Year Top Ten |date=January 2008 |magazine=The Wire |issue=287 |page=37 |location=London |url=https://reader.exacteditions.com/issues/3240/spread/37 |url-access=subscription |via=[[Exact Editions]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> and ''[[Stylus Magazine]]''),<ref>{{cite web | title= Top 50 Albums of 2007|url= http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/pop_playground/top-50-albums-of-2007.htm | work = [[Stylus Magazine]] | date=31 October 2007 | accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref> number&nbsp;seven (''NME''),<ref>{{cite web|title=NME Albums & Tracks of the Year |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/albums/oftheyear |work=[[NME]] |accessdate=17 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061209104947/http://www.nme.com/reviews/albums/oftheyear |archivedate=9 December 2006}}</ref> number&nbsp;six (''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'',<ref>{{cite web | title= Signs of Life 2007: Best Music|url= http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2007/11/signs-of-life-2007-best-music-1.html | work = [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] | date=26 November 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref>{{cite web | title= The best music of 2007|url= http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-best-music-of-2007,2104/ | work=[[The A.V. Club]] | date=12 December 2007 |accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''),<ref>{{cite web | title= The Best (and Worst) Albums of 2007|url= http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20162677_20164091_20166853_4,00.html | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> number&nbsp;four (''The Guardian''<ref>{{cite web | title= 2007's best albums|url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/dec/07/4 | work = [[The Guardian]] | date=7 December 2007 |accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> and ''[[Drowned in Sound]]''),<ref>{{cite magazine| title= DiS's albums of 2007: 5\u20131 (and full top 50)| url= http://www.drownedinsound.com/in_depth/2673307| magazine= [[Drowned in Sound]]| accessdate= 18 December 2008| date= | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090210134452/http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/2673307| archive-date= 10 February 2009| url-status= dead}}</ref> and number&nbsp;three (''Pitchfork'').<ref>{{cite web | title= Top 50 Albums of 2007|url= http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/6753-top-50-albums-of-2007/| publisher = Pitchfork Media | date=18 December 2007 | accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> The album was also listed at number&nbsp;three on ''[[The Village Voice]]''{{'}}s 35th annual ''[[Pazz & Jop]]'' poll.<ref name=\"vvmia07\">{{cite web | title= The 35th Annual Village Voice pazz&jop critics' poll | work=[[The Village Voice]] | url= http://www.villagevoice.com/pazzandjop07/winners.php?type=album | date=24 January 2008|accessdate=14 September 2009 |archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080212030603/http://www.villagevoice.com/pazzandjop07/winners.php?type=album |archivedate = 12 February 2008}}</ref> ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' and ''Rolling Stone'' both named ''Kala'' as their number&nbsp;one album of 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/bests/2007.shtml |title=Best Albums of 2007 \u2013 Music Critics' Year-End Top Ten Lists |publisher=Metacritic. CBS Interactive |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305152451/http://www.metacritic.com/music/bests/2007.shtml |archivedate=5 March 2008 |accessdate=17 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17601851/the_top_50_albums_of_2007 |title=The Top 50 Albums of 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2008 |date=27 December 2007 |first=Robert |last=Christgau |author2=Fricke, David |author3=Hoard, Christian |author4=Sheffield, Rob |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106025129/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17601851/the_top_50_albums_of_2007 |archivedate=6 January 2010 }}</ref> \"Boyz\" was number&nbsp;nine and \"Shells\" number&nbsp;sixty-seven on the same magazine's list of the 100 Best Songs of 2007 and 2008 respectively.<ref name=\"bestsongs\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/24947047/the_100_best_singles_of_2008/17 |title=The 100 Best Songs of 2008 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=25 December 2008 |accessdate=12 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114135/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/24947047/the_100_best_singles_of_2008/17 |archivedate=3 May 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rolling Stone's 100 Best Songs of 2007 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17601363/the_100_best_songs_of_2007/3 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=11 December 2007 |accessdate=14 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417211309/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17601363/the_100_best_songs_of_2007/3 |archivedate=17 April 2009 }}</ref>\nThe album was nominated for the 2007 [[Shortlist Music Prize]].<ref name=web>{{cite web|accessdate=8 January 2010 |url=http://www.shortlistofmusic.com/ |title=(sh\u00f4rt\u2013l\u012dst) |first=Greg |last=Spotts |publisher=Short List |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212014941/http://www.shortlistofmusic.com/ |archivedate=12 February 2013}}</ref> \n\n''Kala'' appears frequently on professional rankings of the greatest albums.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A4238.htm|title=Kala|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> In 2009, ''NME'' placed the album at number&nbsp;seventy-two in its list of the 100 greatest records of the decade,<ref name=\"NMEGreatest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/albums-of-the-decade/158049/page/1|title=The Top 100 Greatest Albums of the Decade|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=4 December 2009|first=Alex|last=Miller}}</ref> and ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked it as the ninth best album of the same period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248017/100_best_albums_of_the_decade/print |title=100 Best Albums of the Decade |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=9 December 2009 |accessdate=3 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106030254/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/31248017/100_best_albums_of_the_decade/print |archivedate=6 January 2010 }}</ref> Christgau named it the decade's best album in his ballot for the magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/list/rs00.php|title=Rolling Stone Ballot: The 00's Best Songs & Albums|publisher=[[Robert Christgau]]|accessdate=31 December 2009|date=24 December 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102174101/http://robertchristgau.com/xg/list/rs00.php|archive-date=2 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2012, ''Rolling Stone'' ranked it at number 393 in a revised edition of their [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]] issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/m-i-a-kala-19691231|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=2 June 2012|title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time: 393 \u2013 M.I.A. \"Kala\"|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604051605/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-20120531/m-i-a-kala-19691231|archivedate=4 June 2012}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[NME]]'' ranked it number 184 in its list of the [[NME's The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/photos/the-500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-200-101-1426258|title=The 500 Greatest Albums Of All Time: 200-101 {{!}} NME|date=2013-10-25|website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> In 2015, the album was ranked number 42 by ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' in its list of the \"The 300 Best Albums of the Past 30 Years (1985-2014)\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2015/05/the-300-best-albums-of-the-past-30-years-1985-2014/|title=The 300 Best Albums of the Past 30 Years (1985-2014)|date=2015-05-11|website=Spin|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=2014 |publisher=Universe|isbn=0-7893-2074-6}}</ref> In 2019, the album was ranked 75th on ''The Guardian'''s 100 Best Albums of the 21st Century list.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/13/100-best-albums-of-the-21st-century |title=The 100 best albums of the 21st century |work=The Guardian |date=13 September 2019 |accessdate=18 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\nBased on such rankings, the aggregate website [[Acclaimed Music]] lists ''Kala'' as the 27th most acclaimed album of the 2000s decade and the 258th most acclaimed album in history.<ref name=\"AM\"/> When asked in March 2020 whether ''Kala'' remains his favorite album of the 21st century, Christgau responded, \"Yup. No contest.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=March 18, 2020|url=https://robertchristgau.substack.com/p/xgau-sez-067|title=Xgau Sez|work=And It Don't Stop|publisher=Substack|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Kala'' debuted at number eighteen on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 29,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hasty |first=Katie |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1049625/high-school-musical-2-hangs-on-atop-billboard-200 |title='High School Musical 2' Hangs on Atop Billboard 200 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=29 August 2007 |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref> It failed to rise above this position but still significantly outperformed the peak position of 190 attained by M.I.A.'s previous album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mia-mn0000388773/awards |title=M.I.A. {{!}} Awards |website=AllMusic |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> It also topped the [[Dance/Electronic Albums|Top Electronic Albums]] chart.<ref name=\"USelectro\"/> The album was certified [[RIAA certification|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on 5&nbsp;March 2010,<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> and by September 2013, it had sold 559,000 copies in the United States.<ref name=\"USsales\">{{cite web |last=Lipshutz |first=Jason |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/5680069/mia-matangi-fall-music-preview-2013 |title=M.I.A., 'Matangi': Fall Music Preview 2013 |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=3 September 2013 |accessdate=6 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe album debuted at number thirty-nine on the [[UK Albums Chart]],<ref name=\"ukchart\"/> and again did not rise above this position, although as in the US this represented an improvement on the chart performance of ''Arular'', which had peaked at number ninety-eight.<ref>{{cite book |last=Roach |first=Martin |year=2009 |title=The Virgin Book of British Hit Albums |publisher=Virgin Books |page=328 |isbn=0-7535-1700-0}}</ref> The album was certified silver by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) on 30 January 2009, denoting sales in excess of 60,000 copies within the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"BPI\"/> In Canada, ''Kala'' was certified gold by the [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] (CRIA).<ref name=\"CRIA\"/> The album also reached the top forty in a number of other countries, including Belgium, Finland, Ireland, Japan, Norway and Sweden.<ref name=\"ultratop\"/><ref name=\"ire\"/><ref name=\"oricon\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = Bamboo Banga\n| writer1 = {{flatlist|\n* [[M.I.A. (rapper)|M.I.A.]]\n* [[Switch (house DJ)|Switch]]\n* [[Jonathan Richman]]\n* [[Ilaiyaraaja]]}}\n| extra1 = {{flatlist|\n* M.I.A.\n* Switch}}\n| length1 = 4:58\n\n| title2 = [[Bird Flu (song)|Bird Flu]]\n| writer2 = {{flatlist|\n* M.I.A.\n* Switch\n* [[R. P. Patnaik]]}}\n| extra2 = {{flatlist|\n* M.I.A.\n* Switch{{ref|a|[a]}}\n}}\n| length2 = 3:24\n\n| title3 = [[Boyz (song)|Boyz]]\n| writer3 = {{flatlist|\n* M.I.A.\n* Switch}}\n| extra3 = {{flatlist|\n* M.I.A.\n* Switch}}\n| length3 = 3:27\n\n| title4 = [[Jimmy (song)|Jimmy]]\n| writer4 = {{flatlist|\n* M.I.A.\n* Switch\n* [[Bappi Lahiri]]}}\n| extra4 = {{flatlist|\n* M.I.A.\n* Swi