{"title_page": "17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry\n|dates= August 18, 1862, to June 10, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment=\n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br>[[Battle of Chancellorsville]]<br>[[Battle of Gettysburg]]<br>[[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br>[[Battle of Spotsylvania]]<br>[[Battle of Cold Harbor]]<br>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br />[[Appomattox Campaign]]\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander =\n| commander1 =George Warren West\n| commander1_label =  [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] \n<!-- Insignia -->\n| image = IIIcorpsbadge1.png\n| caption =1st Division, III Corps\n\n}}\n[[File:17th ME Inf Position Marker.jpg|thumb|17th Maine Infantry position marker at Gettysburg National Military Park]]\n[[File:17th Maine Inf. Vols LCCN2013648710.jpg|thumb|1864, 17th Maine  infantry soldiers, and a regimental band. The photo was taken in Northern Virginia on the day the regiment broke camp to begin its summer campaign. ]]\nThe '''17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry''' was a three-year volunteer infantry regiment from southern Maine that served primarily with the Army of the Potomac in the eastern theater of the American Civil War.\n\n==Service==\nOrganized at Camp King,[[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]], and mustered in for three years' service on August 18, 1862, and was mustered out on June 10, 1865.  Recruits still liable to serve were transferred to [[1st Maine Heavy Artillery Regiment|1st Maine Volunteer Heavy Artillery Regiment]]. The regiment was in answer to the 2 July 2, 1862, call by Lincoln for 300,000 volunteers for three years. The state of Maine's quota was 9,609.<ref name=\"Houghton\">Houghton</ref>\n\nThe regiment was recruited in southern maine from Androscoggin, Cumberland, Franklin, and York counties. As recruits entered training camp, the regiment quickly fleshed out to ten companies, A through K. Upon muster into federal service, each recruit received a federal bounty of $27.00.<ref name=\"Houghton\" /> \n\n===Detailed Service===\n\n====1862====\n* Left State for Washington, D.C., August 21. \n* Attached to Defenses of Washington to October 7, 1862<ref name=\"OoB\">{{Cite web|title = A Compilation of the Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880-1901|url =http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html |website = cdl.library.cornell.edu|accessdate = 2017-04-08}}</ref>. \n* At Upton's Hill, Va., until October 12 \u2014 ''Attached to [[Hiram George Berry|Berry]]'s 3rd Brigade, [[David B. Birney|Birney]]'s 1st Division, [[Joseph Hooker|Hooker]]'s III Corps, [[Ambrose Burnside|Burnside]]'s Army of Potomac'' \n* Edwards Ferry October 12-28. \n* Advance to Warrenton, thence to Falmouth, Va., October 28-November 22. \n* [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] December 12-15.\n** Eastern Bank of Rappahannock December 12-13\n** Fields southwest of Fredericksburg December 13-15\n* To winter encampment, Falmouth VA, 16 December\n\n====1863====\n\n* \"[[Mud March (American Civil War)|Mud March]]\" January 20-24 \n* Back to encampment, Camp Sickles, Falmouth, 25 January\n* [[Chancellorsville Campaign]] April 27-May 6. \u2014 ''Attached to Hayman's 3rd Brigade, Birney's 1st Division, [[Daniel Sickles|Sickle]]'s III Corps, Hooker's Army of Potomac''  \n** The Plank Road, April 29-30 \n** [[Battle of Chancellorsville]] May 1-5. \n* Return to Camp Sickles, 6  May\n* [[Gettysburg campaign|Gettysburg Campaign]] June 13-July 24<ref name=\"Houghton\" />. \n** To Manassas. 11-16 June\n** Centerville, 17-25 June\n** Edward's Ferry, 26 June\n** To Middletown, MD, 27 June\n** To Frederick, MD, 28 June\n** To Taneytown, MD 29 June\n** T0 Emmetsburg, 30 June\n** To Gettysburg, 1 July \n** [[Battle of Gettysburg]] July 2-3. \n** Pursuit of Lee July 5-24. \n** Wapping Heights July 23. \n* Bristoe Campaign October 9-22. \n* Auburn and Bristoe October 14. \n* Advance to line of the Rappahannock November 7-8. \n* Kelly's Ford November 7. \n* Mine Run Campaign November 26-December 2. \n** Payne's Farm November 27. \n** Mine Run November 28-30.\n\n====1864====\n\n* Demonstration on the Rapidan February 6-7, 1864. Campaign from the Rapidan to the James May 3-June 15. Battles of the Wilderness May 5-7. Laurel Hill May 8. Spotsylvania May 8-!2, Po River May 10. Spotsylvania C. H. May 12-21, \"Bloody Angle,\" Assault on the Salient, May 12. Harris Farm, Fredericksburg Road, May 19. North Anna May 23-26. Line of the Pamunkey May 26-28. Totopotomoy May 28-31. Cold Harbor June 1-12. Before Petersburg June 16-19. Siege of Petersburg June 16, 1864, to April 2. 1865. Jerusalem Plank Road June 22-23, 1864. Deep Bottom, north of the James, July 27-28. Mine Explosion, Petersburg, July 30. Demonstration north of the James August 13-20. Strawberry Plains August 14-18. Ream's Station August 25. Poplar Springs Church September 29-October 2. Boydton Plank Road, Hatcher's Run, October 27-28. Raid on Weldon Railroad December 7-11.\n\n====1865====\n\nDabney's Mills February 5-7, 1865. Appomattox Campaign March 28-April 9. South Side Railroad March 29. Boydton Road and White Oak Ridge March 30-31. Fall of Petersburg April 2. Jettersville April 5. Sailor's Creek April 6. High Bridge April 6-7. Farmville April 7. Appomattox C. H. April 9. Surrender of Lee and his army. At Burkesville April 11-May 1. March to Washington, D. C., May 1-15. Grand Review May 23. Mustered out at Bailey's Cross Roads June 4, 1865. Recruits transferred to 1st Maine Heavy Aruntilery. Discharged at Portland, Me., June 10, 1865.\n\n===Armament===\n\n==Casualties and total strength==\nThe 17th Maine enrolled 1,371 men during its existence.<ref>http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/17meinf.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230092433/http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/17meinf.htm |date=2006-12-30 }} State of Maine Civil War Records Website</ref> It lost 12 officers and 116 enlisted men killed in action or died of wounds received in battle and an additional 4 officers and 159 enlisted men died of disease.<ref>http://www.civilwararchive.com/Unreghst/unmeinf1.htm Civil War Archive Website, after Dyer</ref>  31 men died in Confederate prisons.  Total fatalities for the regiment were 370.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">State of Maine Civil War Records Website</ref>\n\n==Commanders==\n* [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] George Warren West\n\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [http://www.civilwarhome.com/gettysburgorderofbattle%28union%29.htm Civilwarhome - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110603055742/http://www.civilwar.org/battlefields/gettysburg/gettysburg-history-articles/order-of-battle-aop-gettysburg.html Civil War Trust - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* Coates, Earl J., and Thomas S. Dean. ''An Introduction to Civil War Small Arms''. Gettysburg, Penn.: [[Thomas Publications]], 1990. {{ISBN|0-939631-25-3}}.\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Eicher, John H. [http://www.gdg.org/Research/OOB/EicherOOB.htm \"Gettysburg Order of Battle\"] at Gettysburg Discussion Group website.\n* {{cite book|author=Flatnes, Oyvind |title=From Musket to Metallic Cartridge: A Practical History of Black Powder Firearms|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/From-Musket-Metallic-Cartridge-Practical/dp/1847975933|year=2013|publisher=Crowood Press|isbn=978-1847975935}}\n* [http://www.gdg.org/research/OOB/Union/gburg_un.html Gettysburg Discussion Group - Union order of battle]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/gett/historyculture/aop-orderofbattle.htm Gettysburg National Military Park - The Army of the Potomac at Gettysburg]\n* Houghton, Edwin B ''The Campaigns of the Seventeenth Maine'' Portland, ME: Short & Loring, 1866\n* Huntington, Tom ''Maine Roads to Gettysburg: How Joshua Chamberlain, Oliver Howard, and 4,000 Men from the Pine Tree State Helped Win the Civil War's Bloodiest Battle''. Mechanicsburg, PA: Stackpole Books, 2018. {{ISBN|0-8117-1840-9}}.\n* Jordan, William B., Jr. ''Red Diamond Regiment: The 17th Maine Infantry, 1862-1865''. Shippensburg, PA: White Mane Pub, 1996. {{ISBN|0-9425-9772-9}}.\n* U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n* [[List of Maine Civil War units]]\n* [[Maine in the American Civil War]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061229160318/http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/3meinf.htm State of Maine Civil War Records Website]\n*[http://www.mainememory.net/bin/Detail?ln=4127 Photograph of the 17th Maine Infantry from the Maine Memory Network]\n\n[[Category:Maine Civil War regiments|17th Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Maine]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-unit-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry\n|dates= August 18, 1862, to June 10, 1865\n|country= [[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[Infantry]]\n|equipment=\n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles=[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br>[[Battle of Chancellorsville]]<br>[[Battle of Gettysburg]]<br>[[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br>[[Battle of Spotsylvania]]<br>[[Battle of Cold Harbor]]<br>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br />[[Appomattox Campaign]]\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| current_commander =\n| commander1 =George Warren West\n| commander1_label =  [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] \n<!-- Insignia -->\n| image = IIIcorpsbadge1.png\n| caption =1st Division, III Corps\n\n}}\n[[File:17th ME Inf Position Marker.jpg|thumb|17th Maine Infantry position marker at Gettysburg National Military Park]]\n[[File:17th Maine Inf. Vols LCCN2013648710.jpg|thumb|1864, 17th Maine  infantry soldiers, and a regimental band. The photo was taken in Northern Virginia on the day the regiment broke camp to begin its summer campaign. ]]\nThe '''17th Regiment Maine Volunteer Infantry''' was a three-year volunteer infantry regiment from southern Maine that served primarily with the Army of the Potomac in the eastern theater of the American Civil War.\n\n==Service==\nOrganized at Camp King,[[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]], and mustered in for three years' service on August 18, 1862, and was mustered out on June 10, 1865.  Recruits still liable to serve were transferred to [[1st Maine Heavy Artillery Regiment|1st Maine Volunteer Heavy Artillery Regiment]]. The regiment was in answer to the 2 July 2, 1862, call by Lincoln for 300,000 volunteers for three years. The state of Maine's quota was 9,609.<ref name=\"Houghton\">Houghton</ref>\n\nThe regiment was recruited in southern maine from Androscoggin, Cumberland, Franklin, and York counties. As recruits entered training camp, the regiment quickly fleshed out to ten companies, A through K. Upon muster into federal service, each recruit received a federal bounty of $27.00.<ref name=\"Houghton\" /> \n\n===Detailed Service===\n\n====1862====\n* Left State for Washington, D.C., August 21. \n* Attached to Defenses of Washington to October 7, 1862<ref name=\"OoB\">{{Cite web|title = A Compilation of the Official Records of the American Civil War of the Union and Confederate Armies, U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880-1901|url =http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html |website = cdl.library.cornell.edu|accessdate = 2017-04-08}}</ref>. \n* At Upton's Hill, Va., until October 12 \u2014 ''Attached to [[Hiram George Berry|Berry]]'s 3rd Brigade, [[David B. Birney|Birney]]'s 1st Division, [[Joseph Hooker|Hooker]]'s III Corps, [[Ambrose Burnside|Burnside]]'s Army of Potomac'' \n* Edwards Ferry October 12-28. \n* Advance to Warrenton, thence to Falmouth, Va., October 28-November 22. \n* [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] December 12-15.\n** Eastern Bank of Rappahannock December 12-13\n** Fields southwest of Fredericksburg December 13-15\n* To winter encampment, Falmouth VA, 16 December\n\n====1863====\n\n* \"[[Mud March (American Civil War)|Mud March]]\" January 20-24 \n* Back to encampment, Camp Sickles, Falmouth, 25 January\n* [[Chancellorsville Campaign]] April 27-May 6. \n** The Plank Road, April 29-30 \n** [[Battle of Chancellorsville]] May 1-5. \n* Return to Camp Sickles, 6  May\n* [[Gettysburg campaign|Gettysburg Campaign]] June 13-July 24<ref name=\"Houghton\" />. \n** To Manassas. 11-16 June\n** Centerville, 17-25 June\n** Edward's Ferry, 26 June\n** To Middletown, MD, 27 June\n** To Frederick, MD, 28 June\n** To Taneytown, MD 29 June\n** T0 Emmetsburg, 30 June\n** To Gettysburg, 1 July \n** [[Battle of Gettysburg]] July 2-3. \n** Pursuit of Lee July 5-24. \n** Wapping Heights July 23. \n* Bristoe Campaign October 9-22. \n* Auburn and Bristoe October 14. \n* Advance to line of the Rappahannock November 7-8. \n* Kelly's Ford November 7. \n* Mine Run Campaign November 26-December 2. \n** Payne's Farm November 27. \n** Mine Run November 28-30.\n\n====1864====\n\n* Demonstration on the Rapidan February 6-7, 1864. Campaign from the Rapidan to the James May 3-June 15. Battles of the Wilderness May 5-7. Laurel Hill May 8. Spotsylvania May 8-!2, Po River May 10. Spotsylvania C. H. May 12-21, \"Bloody Angle,\" Assault on the Salient, May 12. Harris Farm, Fredericksburg Road, May 19. North Anna May 23-26. Line of the Pamunkey May 26-28. Totopotomoy May 28-31. Cold Harbor June 1-12. Before Petersburg June 16-19. Siege of Petersburg June 16, 1864, to April 2. 1865. Jerusalem Plank Road June 22-23, 1864. Deep Bottom, north of the James, July 27-28. Mine Explosion, Petersburg, July 30. Demonstration north of the James August 13-20. Strawberry Plains August 14-18. Ream's Station August 25. Poplar Springs Church September 29-October 2. Boydton Plank Road, Hatcher's Run, October 27-28. Raid on Weldon Railroad December 7-11.\n\n====1865====\n\nDabney's Mills February 5-7, 1865. Appomattox Campaign March 28-April 9. South Side Railroad March 29. Boydton Road and White Oak Ridge March 30-31. Fall of Petersburg April 2. Jettersville April 5. Sailor's Creek April 6. High Bridge April 6-7. Farmville April 7. Appomattox C. H. April 9. Surrender of Lee and his army. At Burkesville April 11-May 1. March to Washington, D. C., May 1-15. Grand Review May 23. Mustered out at Bailey's Cross Roads June 4, 1865. Recruits transferred to 1st Maine Heavy Aruntilery. Discharged at Portland, Me., June 10, 1865.\n\n===Armament===\n\n==Casualties and total strength==\nThe 17th Maine enrolled 1,371 men during its existence.<ref>http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/17meinf.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230092433/http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/17meinf.htm |date=2006-12-30 }} State of Maine Civil War Records Website</ref> It lost 12 officers and 116 enlisted men killed in action or died of wounds received in battle and an additional 4 officers and 159 enlisted men died of disease.<ref>http://www.civilwararchive.com/Unreghst/unmeinf1.htm Civil War Archive Website, after Dyer</ref>  31 men died in Confederate prisons.  Total fatalities for the regiment were 370.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">State of Maine Civil War Records Website</ref>\n\n==Commanders==\n* [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] George Warren West\n\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [http://www.civilwarhome.com/gettysburgorderofbattle%28union%29.htm Civilwarhome - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110603055742/http://www.civilwar.org/battlefields/gettysburg/gettysburg-history-articles/order-of-battle-aop-gettysburg.html Civil War Trust - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* Coates, Earl J., and Thomas S. Dean. ''An Introduction to Civil War Small Arms''. Gettysburg, Penn.: [[Thomas Publications]], 1990. {{ISBN|0-939631-25-3}}.\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Eicher, John H. [http://www.gdg.org/Research/OOB/EicherOOB.htm \"Gettysburg Order of Battle\"] at Gettysburg Discussion Group website.\n* {{cite book|author=Flatnes, Oyvind |title=From Musket to Metallic Cartridge: A Practical History of Black Powder Firearms|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/From-Musket-Metallic-Cartridge-Practical/dp/1847975933|year=2013|publisher=Crowood Press|isbn=978-1847975935}}\n* [http://www.gdg.org/research/OOB/Union/gburg_un.html Gettysburg Discussion Group - Union order of battle]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/gett/historyculture/aop-orderofbattle.htm Gettysburg National Military Park - The Army of the Potomac at Gettysburg]\n* Houghton, Edwin B ''The Campaigns of the Seventeenth Maine'' Portland, ME: Short & Loring, 1866\n* Huntington, Tom ''Maine Roads to Gettysburg: How Joshua Chamberlain, Oliver Howard, and 4,000 Men from the Pine Tree State Helped Win the Civil War's Bloodiest Battle''. Mechanicsburg, PA: Stackpole Books, 2018. {{ISBN|0-8117-1840-9}}.\n* Jordan, William B., Jr. ''Red Diamond Regiment: The 17th Maine Infantry, 1862-1865''. Shippensburg, PA: White Mane Pub, 1996. {{ISBN|0-9425-9772-9}}.\n* U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n* [[List of Maine Civil War units]]\n* [[Maine in the American Civil War]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061229160318/http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/3meinf.htm State of Maine Civil War Records Website]\n*[http://www.mainememory.net/bin/Detail?ln=4127 Photograph of the 17th Maine Infantry from the Maine Memory Network]\n\n[[Category:Maine Civil War regiments|17th Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Maine]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-unit-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1863", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/17th_Regiment_Maine_Volunteer_Infantry"}
{"title_page": "Sokol Cikalleshi", "text_new": "{{short description|Albanian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Sokol Cikalleshi\n| image = 20160326 AUT ALB 0007 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = 250\n| caption = Cikalleshi with [[Albania national football team|Albania]] in March 2016\n| fullname = Sokol Cikalleshi\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|7|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Kavaj\u00eb]], [[Albania]]\n| height = 1.87 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Akhisar Belediyespor]]\n| clubnumber = 37\n| youthyears1 = 2002\u20132008\n| youthclubs1 = [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132013\n| clubs1 = [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]]\n| caps1 = 56\n| goals1 = 11\n| years2 = 2011\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[KF Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 4\n| goals2 = 3\n| years3 = 2012\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[KF Tirana|Tirana]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 13\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2012\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Incheon United]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 6\n| goals4 = 4\n| years5 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs5 = [[FK Kuk\u00ebsi|Kuk\u00ebsi]]\n| caps5 = 30\n| goals5 = 17\n| years6 = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs6 = [[RNK Split|Split]]\n| caps6 = 32\n| goals6 = 18\n| years7 = 2015\u20132017\n| clubs7 = [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]]\n| caps7 = 31\n| goals7 = 6\n| years8 = 2017\n| clubs8 = \u2192 [[Akhisar Belediyespor]] (loan)\n| caps8 = 14\n| goals8 = 7\n| years9 = 2017\u20132019\n| clubs9 = [[Osmanl\u0131spor]]\n| caps9 = 26\n| goals9 = 14\n| years10 = 2018\u20132019\n| clubs10 = \u2192 [[G\u00f6ztepe S.K.|G\u00f6ztepe]] (loan)\n| caps10 = 7\n| goals10 = 4\n| years11 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs11 = [[Akhisar Belediyespor]]\n| caps11 = 12\n| goals11 = 8\n\n| nationalyears1 = 2008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Albania national under-19 football team|Albania U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2009\n| nationalteam2 = [[Albania national under-20 football team|Albania U20]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 2\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2009\u20132011\n| nationalteam3 = [[Albania national under-21 football team|Albania U21]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 3\n| nationalgoals3 = 1\n| nationalyears4 = 2014\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Albania national football team|Albania]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 35\n| nationalgoals4 = 6\n| medaltemplates = \n| club-update = 16 May 2019\n| nationalteam-update = 14 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Sokol Cikalleshi''' ({{IPA-sq|'s\u0254k\u0254l 'tsika\u026b\u025b\u0283i}}; born 27 July 1990) is an Albanian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for Turkish club [[Akhisar Belediyespor]] and the [[Albania national football team|Albania national team]].\n\nHe made his professional debut in 2007 as a 17-year-old with his hometown club [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]], and would then go on loan to [[KF Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], [[KF Tirana|Tirana]] and South Korean side [[Incheon United]] between 2011 and 2012. He joined [[FK Kuk\u00ebsi|Kuk\u00ebsi]] in 2013 and scored 22 goals in all competitions during the 2013\u201314 campaign, where he gained the attention of the [[Albania national football team|Albania national team]] setup as well as Croatian side [[RNK Split]] who signed the player in 2014 for a reported fee of \u20ac100,000. He was the club's top goalscorer during the 2014\u201315 campaign, netting 13 times in all competitions before joining Turkish club [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]] for a \u20ac1.8 million fee in 2015.\n\nHe was first called up to the [[Albania national football team|Albania national team]] by [[Gianni De Biasi]] and he made his debut on 31 May 2014 against [[Romania national football team|Romania]]. Since making his debut he has been a regular member of the national side, and he has earned  33 caps since 2014 and scored 6 goals and assisted 1.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Besa Kavaj\u00eb===\nCikalleshi joined his hometown club [[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]] in 2002 as a 12-year-old and he progressed through the youth ranks at the club,<ref>[http://www.fshf.org/garat/components/lojtar.php?player_id=214469 Sokol Cikalleshi profile] at [[FSHF]].org</ref> until he made his professional debut at the age of 17 on the final day of the [[2007\u201308 Albanian Superliga]] against local rivals [[Teuta Durr\u00ebs]], a match in which he came on as a half time substitute in a 5\u20133 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.match.teuta-durres.besa-kavaje.255655.en.html |title=Teuta Durr\u00ebs 3\u20135 Besa Kavaj\u00eb |publisher=Footballdatabase |accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> In the following season he was an important member of the club's under-19s, as he captained the side to the national championship title in a season where he also made 10 league appearances for the senior side, including 2 starts. Under [[Shp\u00ebtim Duro]], Cikalleshi became a regular first team member during the 2009\u201310 campaign, where he was part of strike force that included [[Daniel Xhafaj]] and [[Vioresin Sinani]], who are two of the most prolific strikers in Albanian football history. He made 27 league appearances and scored twice, with his first professional goal coming against [[Shkumbini Peqin]] on 29 August 2011 in the [[Albanian Superliga]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.match.shkumbini-peqin.besa-kavaje.515631.en.html |title=Shkumbini Peqin 1\u20132 Besa Kavaj\u00eb |publisher=Footballdatabase |accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> and he also went on to score against [[Vllaznia Shkod\u00ebr]] later in the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2009/11/29/albania/super-league/ks-vllaznia-shkoder/ks-besa-kavaje/827869/ |title=Vllaznia Shkod\u00ebr 2\u20133 Besa Kavaj\u00eb |publisher=Soccerway |accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> The 2009\u201310 campaign proved to be one of the club's most successful ever season, as they finished runners-up in the Albanian Superliga behind [[Dinamo Tirana]] and won the [[Albanian Cup]] for only the second time in history. Cikalleshi played a significant role in the club's cup winning run, as he made 8 appearances and scored twice, including the winning goal in the semi final against [[Shkumbini Peqin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.coupe.shkumbini-peqin.besa-kavaje.110145.en.html |title=Shkumbini Peqin 0\u20131 Besa Kavaj\u00eb |publisher=Footballdatabase |accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> that sent Besa Kavaj\u00eb to the final, which was won against Vllaznia Shkod\u00ebr.\n\n====Loan to Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb====\nHe agreed to join [[KF Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb]] on a 6-month loan deal ahead of the opening of the January 1transfer window, and travelled with the rest of the squad to [[Antalya]], [[Turkey]] for their mid season training camp.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/godet-skenderbeu-presidenti-agim-zeqo-arrin-akordin-me-cikalleshin/|title=\"Godet\" Sk\u00ebnderbeu, Zeqo arrin akordin me Cikalleshin|trans-title=Sk\u00ebnderbeu \"strikes\", Zeqo reaches the argument with Cikalleshi|publisher=Panorama Sport|language=Albanian|date=24 December 2011|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Tirana====\nCikalleshi joined [[KF Tirana|Tirana]] on loan until the end of the 2011\u201312 season on 27 January 2012 following a successful trial at the club, claiming it to be the \"chance of a lifetime\" to have the chance to play for the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportekspres.com/contenti.aspx?id=542&idd=&iddd=&idjadok=18763|title=Gjata firmos p\u00ebr nj\u00eb vit e gjysm\u00eb|language=Albanian|publisher=Sport Ekspres|accessdate=24 January 2016|date=27 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120719131025/http://sportekspres.com/contenti.aspx?id=542&idd=&iddd=&idjadok=18763|archivedate=19 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama-sport.com/merkaro-ne-sulm-flamurtari-largon-hysen-cikalleshi-te-tirana/|title=Flamurtari largon Hys\u00ebn, Cikalleshi huazohet te Tirana|author=Feriz Ferizaj|language=Albanian|publisher=Panorama Sport|accessdate=24 January 2016|date=27 January 2012}}</ref> He made his debut for the club in the [[Albanian Cup]] against [[KF Bylis Ballsh|Bylis Ballsh]] on 29 January, where he came on as a substitute in the 63rd minute for [[Klodian Duro]] in the goalless draw.<ref>[https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2012/01/29/albania/cup/ks-bylis-ballsh/kf-tirana/1241411/ Bylis Ballsh 0-0 KF Tirana] Soccerway</ref>\n\n====Loan to Incheon United====\nIn July 2012, Cikalleshi joined South Korean [[K-League]] club [[Incheon United FC]] on a 6-month loan deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama-sport.com/firmos-ne-kore-cikalleshi-ja-detajet-e-kontrates/|title=Firmos n\u00eb Kore Cikalleshi, ja detajet e kontrat\u00ebs|trans-title=Cikalleshi signs in Korea, here's the details of contract|author=Feriz Ferizaj|publisher=Panorama Sport|language=Albanian|accessdate=14 July 2012|date=25 November 2015}}</ref> During his time at ''Blue-Blacks'', Cikalleshi made six appearances, only two of them as a starter, collecting 193 minutes in the process.\n\n===Kuk\u00ebsi===\nIn August 2013, Cikalleshi joined [[FK Kuk\u00ebsi]] club on a one-year contract. He made his debut with the club on 4 September 2013 during the 1\u20130 shock lose against the newcomers of [[KF Lushnja|Lushnja]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama-sport.com/lushnja-rigjen-superioren-e-ben-sefte-ndaj-nenkampioneve/|title=Nj\u00eb debutues n\u00eb Superiore likujdon Kuk\u00ebsin, Lushnja e fillon me fitore rikthimin n\u00eb elit\u00eb|publisher=Panorama Sport|language=Albanian|author=Armand Nezha|accessdate=4 September 2013|date=4 September 2013}}</ref> He opened his scoring account eight weeks later where he scored during the 2\u20131 away lose against [[Flamurtari Vlor\u00eb]], which was followed by another goal in the next week at [[KF La\u00e7i|La\u00e7i]], where Kuk\u00ebsi won in the very last seconds thanks to a penalty.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama-sport.com/ringjallet-kukesi-fiton-me-permbysje-laci-i-nices-peson-humbjen-e-pare-ne-shtepi/|title=\"Ringjallet\" dhe Kuk\u00ebsi, fiton me p\u00ebrmbysje. La\u00e7i i Nic\u00ebs p\u00ebson humbjen e par\u00eb n\u00eb sht\u00ebpi|author=Vladimir Prenga|language=Albanian|work=Panorama Sport|accessdate=3 November 2013|date=3 November 2013}}</ref> On 6 November 2013, in the returning leg of the first round of [[2013\u201314 Albanian Cup]], Cikalleshi scored in a 5\u20130 thrashing of [[Naft\u00ebtari Ku\u00e7ov\u00eb]], helping Kuk\u00ebsi to advance in the next round with the aggregate 6\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama-sport.com/goleade-e-kukesit-ndaj-kucovareve-demtohet-portieri-halili/|title=Golead\u00eb e Kuk\u00ebsit ndaj ku\u00e7ovar\u00ebve, d\u00ebmtohet portieri Halili|author=Jonuz Halla\u00e7i|language=Albanian|work=Panorama Sport|accessdate=6 November 2013|date=6 November 2013}}</ref> He scored for the fourth consecutive match, this time against his former side [[KF Tirana]] helping Kuk\u00ebsi to prevail 2\u20131 at [[Zeqir Ymeri Stadium]]; he was later selected \"Man of the Match\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama-sport.com/kategoria-superiore-nisen-ndeshjet-e-javes-se-11-te/|title=Kuk\u00ebsi fundos Tiran\u00ebn, Gallo drejt shkarkimit|author1=Jonuz Halla\u00e7i|author2=Adela Merko|language=Albanian|work=Panorama Sport|accessdate=10 November 2013|date=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===RNK Split===\nFollowing FK Kuk\u00ebsi's elimination in the [[Europa League]], on 16 July 2014 Cikalleshi signed for Croatian side [[RNK Split]] on a three-year contract for a fee of \u20ac100.000.<ref name=\"Split\">{{cite news|url=http://borozani.com/artikulli/cikalleshi-nga-kukesi-ne-split|title=Cikalleshi nga Kuk\u00ebsi ne Split|trans-title=Cikalleshi from Kuk\u00ebsi to Split|publisher=Borozani.com|language=Albanian|date=17 July 2014|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref> He was presented on the same day where he choose the squad number 99.<ref name=\"Split\"/> However, Kuk\u00ebsi claimed that they would not give Cikalleshi permission to play, as his documents were still at the club. The club also added that the player has still a year remaining in his contract, and that they would send the case to [[FIFA]] and [[UEFA]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/cikalleshi-firmos-per-tre-vite-te-kroatet-e-rnk-split-kukesi-e-kercenon/#ixzz37ofsavVN|title=Cikalleshi firmos tre vite te Split, Kuk\u00ebsi e k\u00ebrc\u00ebnon|trans-title=Cikalleshi signs for three years with Split, Kuk\u00ebsi threats|publisher=Panorama Sport|language=Albanian|date=17 July 2014|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 August he scored his first goal with RNK Split in a match against [[NK Hrvace]], valid for the [[2014\u201315 Croatian Football Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/cikalleshi-gol-dhe-asist-te-spliti/|title=Cikalleshi, gol dhe asist te Spliti|trans-title=Cikalleshi, goal and assist at Split|publisher=Panorama Sport|language=Albanian|date=19 August 2014|accessdate=1 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir===\n[[File:Sokol Cikalleshi.jpg|thumb|right|Cikalleshi with [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]] in 2016]]\nOn 6 June 2015, RNK Split accepted the \u20ac1.8 million bid of Turkish side [[\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir F.K.|\u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir]] to transfer Cikalleshi to the [[S\u00fcper Lig]] club.<ref>[http://www.panorama-sport.com/2015/06/cikalleshi-tek-istanbul-ne-turqi/ Cikalleshi, tek Istanbul n\u00eb Turqi] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619195621/http://www.panorama-sport.com/2015/06/cikalleshi-tek-istanbul-ne-turqi/ |date=19 June 2015 }} [[Panorama Sport]]</ref> Ten days later Cikalleshi was presented to the club where he signed a 4-years contract.<ref>[http://sportal.al/shqiperi/kuqezi/item/6808-prezantohet-sokol-cikalleshi.html Prezantohet Sokol Cikalleshi] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619175250/http://sportal.al/shqiperi/kuqezi/item/6808-prezantohet-sokol-cikalleshi.html |date=19 June 2015 }} Sportal.al</ref>\n\n====Loan at Akhisar Belediyespor====\nIn January 2017 Cikalleshi was loaned to fellow [[S\u00fcper Lig]] side [[Akhisar Belediyespor]] until the end of the season. He made his debut few days later against [[G\u00fcm\u00fc\u015fhanespor]] valid for the [[Turkish Cup]] playing as a starter in a 3\u20131 win with Akhisar Belediyespor progressing through the quarter-finals.<ref>[http://sportekspres.com/cikalleshi-e-nis-mbare/ Cikalleshi e nis mbar\u00eb] [[Sport Ekspres]]</ref> He scored his first goal on 13 March 2017 against [[Trabzonspor]] in the 11th minute for the opening goal of the match which eventually finished in the 1\u20133 loss as opponent overturned in the second-half.<ref>[http://sportekspres.com/edhe-cikalleshi-ia-ben-bam/ Edhe Cikalleshi ia b\u00ebn \"bam\"] [[Sport Ekspres]]</ref><ref>[https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/03/13/turkey/super-lig/akhisar-belediye-gs/trabzonspor/2291357/ Akhisar Belediyespor vs. Trabzonspor - 13 March 2017] Soccerway</ref> On 1 April 2017 Cikalleshi scored 1 goal against his owning team \u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir in the 90'+4-minute to give his side the 2\u20131 victory.<ref>[http://www.supersport.al/cikalleshi-ne-forme-supergol-te-akhisar/ Cikalleshi n\u00eb form\u00eb, supergol te Akhisar] [[SuperSport Albania]]</ref> On 23 April 2017 Cikalleshi scored 1 goal and provided 1 assist against [[Bursaspor]] in a 5\u20131 victory.<ref>[http://www.supersport.al/cikalleshi-gol-dhe-asist-ne-fitoren-e-akhisar/ Cikalleshi gol dhe asist n\u00eb fitoren e Akhisar] [[SuperSport Albania]]</ref> In the next game week Cikalleshi gave 2 assist for all team's goals scored against [[Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa S.K.|Kas\u0131mpa\u015fa]] in a 2\u20130 victory, which made Akhisar Belediyespor to secure standing in the S\u00fcper Lig for next season.<ref>[http://sportekspres.com/cikalleshi-floriri-i-akisarit/ Cikalleshi, \"floriri\" i Akisarit] [[Sport Ekspres]]</ref> On 8 May 2017 Cikalleshi scored two fast goals between 3 minutes and made also a shoot which caused an own goal by a [[Gaziantepspor]] defender. Akhisar Belediyespor took a glorious 6\u20130 victory.<ref>[http://sportekspres.com/sulltan-cikalleshi-gola-e-rekord-nese-luaj-rregullisht/ Sulltan Cikalleshi, gola e rekord: N\u00ebse luaj rregullisht\u2026] [[Sport Ekspres]]</ref> Cikalleshi scored his 6th goal on 22 May 2017 against [[Alanyaspor]] in a 3\u20130 victory.<ref>[http://www.supersport.al/cikalleshi-tjeter-gol-ne-fitoren-e-akhisarit/ Cikalleshi, tjet\u00ebr gol n\u00eb fitoren e Akhisarit] [[SuperSport Albania]]</ref>\n\n====Return====\nCikalleshi was included in the squad list to participate in the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#Third qualifying round|2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League Third qualifying round]].<ref>[http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/cikalleshi-perfshihet-ne-listen-e-liges-se-kampioneve-kace-drejt-rivaleve-te-iraklisit/ Cikalleshi p\u00ebrfshihet n\u00eb list\u00ebn e Lig\u00ebs s\u00eb Kampioneve, Ka\u00e7e drejt rival\u00ebve t\u00eb Iraklisit] [[Panorama Sport]]</ref>\n\n===Osmanl\u0131spor===\nOn 28 August 2017 Cikalleshi signed for fellow [[S\u00fcper Lig]] side [[Osmanl\u0131spor]] a 3-years contract, transferring from \u0130stanbul Ba\u015fak\u015fehir for a fee of \u20ac2 million and will earn \u20ac2.5 million per season.<ref name=\"Osmanilspor\" >[http://www.supersport.al/cikalleshi-per-kombetaren-githmone-maksimumin/ Cikalleshi: P\u00ebr komb\u00ebtaren githmon\u00eb maksimumin] [[SuperSport Albania]]</ref> He made his debut in the 4th game week against [[G\u00f6ztepe S.K.|G\u00f6ztepe]] on 10 September 2017 coming on as a substitute at half-time in a 0\u20132 loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/cikalleshi-debuton-nga-stoli-roshit-nuk-i-sigurojne-minuta-as-golat-me-kombetaren/|title=Cikalleshi debuton nga stoli, Roshit nuk i sigurojn\u00eb minuta as golat me komb\u00ebtaren|trans-title=Cikalleshi debuts from the bench, Roshi does not provide minutes even his goals with the national team|publisher=[[Panorama Sport]]|language=Albanian|date=10 September 2017|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> Cikalleshi started the 2018 in a fenomenal way as he was given a starting place in the [[2017\u201318 Turkish Cup#Round of 16#Second Leg|2017\u201318 Turkish Cup round of 16 second Leg]] match against [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]] in which he managed to score twice respectively in the 86th minute to balance the score only 3 minutes after disadvantage and in the 88th minute to give his side the 2\u20131 victory; however his goals weren't enough Be\u015fikta\u015f advanced further after winning the first leg 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportekspres.com/cfare-starti-cikalleshi-2-gola-beshiktashit/|title=\u00c7far\u00eb starti Cikalleshi, 2 gola Beshiktashit!|trans-title=What a start by Cikalleshi, 2 goals against Besiktas!|publisher=[[Sport Ekspres]]|language=Albanian|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=17 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Akhisar Belediyespor===\nOn 16 January 2019, Cikalleshi made a surprise return to Turkish top flight by signing with [[Akhisar Belediyespor]], whom he had a successful, albeit short spell in 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazeta-shqip.com/lajme/2019/01/17/sokol-cikalleshi-transferohet-tek-klubi-turk/|title=Sokol Cikalleshi transferohet tek klubi turk|trans-title=Sokol Cikalleshi transferred to Turkish club|publisher=Gazeta Shqip|language=Albanian|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref> He signed a contract until June 2022 and was given squad number 37.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.supersport.al/befason-sokol-cikalleshi-transferohet-tek-akhisari/|title=Befason Sokol Cikalleshi, transferohet tek Akhisari|trans-title=Sokol Cikalleshi surprises, transferred to Akhisar|publisher=Gazeta Shqip|language=Albanian|author=Adi Metaliu|date=17 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref> In his first game two days later, Cikalleshi played in the second half and scored his team's lone goal in a 1\u20133 home defeat to [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/video-cikalleshi-i-pabesueshem-shenon-per-akhisarsporin-ne-ndeshjen-e-pare-pas-rikthimit/|title=VIDEO/ Cikalleshi i pabesuesh\u00ebm, sh\u00ebnon p\u00ebr Akhisarsporin n\u00eb ndeshjen e par\u00eb pas rikthimit|trans-title=Video/ Cikalleshi unbelievable, scores for Akhisar in the first match after returning|publisher=Panorama Sport|language=Albanian|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth===\nCikalleshi has been a former [[Albania national youth football team|Albania youth international]], representing [[Albania national under-19 football team|under-19]], [[Albania national under-20 football team|-20]] and [[Albania national under-21 football team|-21]] levels.\n\nHe was part of Albania under-19 squad in the [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification|qualifiers]] of [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]]. His first appearance with under-19 squad occurred on 10 October 2008 in the matchday 2 of Group 5 against [[Serbia national under-19 football team|Serbia]] which finished in a 5\u20130 away loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/fixturesresults/round=15216/match=302179/index.html|title=Serbia 5-0 Albania|publisher=UEFA.com|date=10 October 2008|accessdate=13 October 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120708013055/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under19/fixturesresults/round=15216/match=302179/index.html|archivedate=8 July 2012}}</ref> He went on to make another appearance as Albania finished [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification#Group 9|Group 9]] in the last position.\n\nIn June 2009, Cikalleshi was called up by manager of [[Albania national under-20 football team|Albania under-20 side]] [[Artan Bushati]] to be part of the team at [[Football at the 2009 Mediterranean Games|2009 Mediterranean Games]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arkivalajmeve.com/Peskara-2009-Shqiperia-zbardh-listen-e-futbollisteve.260840/|title=Peskara 2009, Shqip\u00ebria zbardh list\u00ebn e futbollist\u00ebve|trans-title=Pescara 2009, Albania unveils the list of footballers|publisher=Arkiva Shqiptare e Lajmeve|language=Albanian|date=17 June 2009|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref> He played as a starter in both matches of [[Football at the 2009 Mediterranean Games#Group D|Group D]]; in the first, a 1\u20132 loss to [[Tunisia national under-20 football team|Tunisia]], he played for 70 minutes<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722045149/http://www.pescara2009.it/results/pdf/FB/FB_C73_FB040000400002ENG.pdf ALB - TUN 1:2 (1:2)] Wayback Machine</ref> and in the second he played the full match in a 0\u20133 loss to [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain]] which brought the elimination from the tournament.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722045226/http://www.pescara2009.it/results/pdf/FB/FB_C73_FB040000400003ENG.pdf ESP - ALB 3:0 (2:0)] Wayback Machine</ref>\n\nCikalleshi then was part of under-21 squad for the [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualifiers]] of [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] where Albania was placed in [[2011 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification Group 10|Group 10]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2011/teams/team=200002/matches/index.html|title=Under-21 2011 - History - Albania|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> Cikalleshi made his competitive debut on 13 November 2009 in the matchday 6 against [[Austria national under-21 football team|Austria]], entering in the last moments as Albania drew 2\u20132.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2011/matches/round=2000006/match=2000243/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Austria avoid a spot of bother|publisher=UEFA.com|date=13 November 2009|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> Later on 4 September 2010, with Albania already eliminated, Cikalleshi played his first match as starter in the final matchday against [[Azerbaijan national under-21 football team|Azerbaijan]], scoring a goal by unable to avoid the 3\u20132 away loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2011/matches/round=2000006/match=2000250/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Azerbaijan record overdue win against Albania|publisher=UEFA.com|author=Abbas Zahidi|date=4 September 2010|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref> Albania finished Group 10 in the 4th position with only 4 points from 8 matches.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2011/standings/round=2000006/group=2000017/index.html|title=Under-21 2011 - History - Standings|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Senior===\nAfter his good performances with [[FK Kuk\u00ebsi|Kuk\u00ebsi]] in the 2013\u201314 season, Cikalleshi received his first call up at the [[Albania national football team|Albania senior squad]] by coach [[Gianni De Biasi]] for friendlies against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in May and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] & [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] in June 2014. He made his international debut on 31 May in the 1\u20130 away loss to Romania, playing in the first half before leaving for [[Shk\u00eblzen Gashi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/prova-e-pare-e-pergatitjeve-te-kuqezinjve-per-euro-2016/|title=\"Vet\u00ebvrasje\" n\u00eb fund, kuqezinjt\u00eb munden nga Rumania|trans-title=\"Suicide\" at the end, red&black beaten by Romania|publisher=[[Panorama Sport]]|language=Albanian|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nCikalleshi was called-up regularly by the coach [[Gianni De Biasi]] in the team's successful [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying Group I|UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-3268784/Jubilant-Albania-defy-odds-reach-maiden-European-Championship.html|title=Jubilant Albania defy the odds to reach a maiden European Championship|date=11 October 2015|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> He was the main striker, collecting 7 appearances but failing to score any goal. On 16 November 2015, Cikalleshi came off the bench to score his first international goal for Albania in the 94th minute to give Albania the 2\u20132 draw in a friendly home against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]], in the last international match at [[Qemal Stafa Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ikub.al/Lajme/15/11/16/Shqiperi-Gjeorgji-mbyllet-2-2-Me-ne-fund-shenon-Cikalleshi-0257.aspx|title=Shqip\u00ebri-Gjeorgji mbyllet 2\u20132, m\u00eb n\u00eb fund sh\u00ebnon Cikalleshi|accessdate=21 November 2015|date=16 November 2015|language=Albanian|work=Iklub.al}}</ref>\n\nCikalleshi lost his place in the starting lineup from the beginning of 2016 due to good running form of fellow striker [[Armando Sadiku]]. He was however, named in Albania's preliminary 27-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2016]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=2366548.html|title=De Biasi leaves out Albanian top scorer Salihi|publisher=UEFA|author=Fatjon Pandovski|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=30 May 2016}}</ref> and in Albania's final 23-man UEFA Euro 2016 squad on 31 May.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://euro.fshf.org/de-biasi-shpall-listen-zyrtare-te-euro-2016/|title=De Biasi shpall list\u00ebn zyrtare t\u00eb Euro 2016|publisher=[[FSHF]]|date=31 May 2016|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref> Cikalleshi made his first appearance against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] in the opening match, entering in the last 15 minutes as Albania suffered a 1\u20130 loss.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/albania-0-1-switzerland-fabian-8044919|title=Albania 0-1 Switzerland: Fabian Schar's fourth-minute header sinks 10-man Albania in Group A clash|work=Mirror|date=11 June 2016|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> Those were the only minutes that his played during the campaign as he was an unused substitute in the next matches against [[France national football team|France]] and [[Romania national football team|Romania]]. Albania finished the group in the third position with three points and with a goal difference \u20132, and was ranked last in the third-placed teams, which eventually eliminated them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/albania-out-euro-2016-after-portugal-draw-hungary|title=Albania out of Euro 2016 after Portugal draw with Hungary|publisher=Fourfourtwo.com|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nCikalleshi was barely used in Albania's [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group G|2018 FIFA World Cup qualifying]] campaign. He made only 3 appearances, only one as starter, collecting 132 minutes without scoring. In September 2017, he was called-up and later omitted by manager [[Christian Panucci]] for the matches against [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]] and [[Macedonia national football team|Macedonia]] as he asked permission to conclude his transfer at [[Osmanl\u0131spor]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fshf.org/index.php/sq/lajme/5774-trajneri-panucci-shpall-listen-e-lojtareve-per-ndeshjet-zyrtare-eleminatore-kunder-lihtenshteinit-dhe-maqedonise|title=Trajneri Panucci shpall list\u00ebn e lojtar\u00ebve p\u00ebr ndeshjet zyrtare eleminatore kund\u00ebr Lihtenshteinit dhe Maqedonis\u00eb|trans-title=Manager Panucci announces the players list for the official qualifying matches against Liechtenstein and Macedonia|publisher=[[Albanian Football Association|FSHF]]|language=Albanian|date=25 August 2017|accessdate=25 August 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827205028/http://fshf.org/index.php/sq/lajme/5774-trajneri-panucci-shpall-listen-e-lojtareve-per-ndeshjet-zyrtare-eleminatore-kunder-lihtenshteinit-dhe-maqedonise|archivedate=27 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Osmanilspor\"/>\n\n==Style of play==\nCikalleshi is a versatile attacking player who is known for his goalscoring ability and his aerial prowess. He is also a very strong player on the ball who is capable with both feet. In addition to that, Cikalleshi is also a great player in the air and considered as an aerial threat.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 12 October 2017, Cikalleshi become a father for the first time when his wife gave birth to the couple's first daughter, named Rajna.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.panorama.com.al/sport/cikalleshi-behet-baba-per-here-te-pare-perjetova-parajsen-e-kesaj-bote/|title=Cikalleshi b\u00ebhet baba p\u00ebr her\u00eb t\u00eb par\u00eb: P\u00ebrjetova parajs\u00ebn e k\u00ebsaj bote!|trans-title=Cikalleshi becomes father for the first time: I experienced the paradise of this world|publisher=Panorama Sport|language=Albanian|date=12 October 2017|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|19 January 2019}}<ref name=\"Soccerway\">{{Soccerway|sokol-cikalleshi/81658|accessdate=17 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.sokol.cikalleshi.53572.en.html|title=Football : Sokol Cikalleshi|publisher=Football Database|accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=player&id=81658|title=Profile of Sokol Cikalleshi|publisher=Scoresway|accessdate=13 January 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Club statistics\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA|Europe]]<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">Including continental competitions, such as [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">Including other competitions, such as [[Albanian Supercup]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|[[Besa Kavaj\u00eb]]\n|[[2007\u201308 Albanian Superliga|2007\u201308]]\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Albanian Superliga]]\n|1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Albanian Superliga|2008\u201309]]\n|10||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||0\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Albanian Superliga|2009\u201310]]\n|27||2||6||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||4\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Albanian Superliga|2010\u201311]]\n|15||6||1||1||1<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UEL\">All appearance(s) in [[UEFA Europa League]]</ref>||0||1<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">Including one appearance in [[2010 Albanian Supercup|Albanian Supercup]]</ref>||0||19||7\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Albanian Superliga|2012\u201313]]\n|4||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||3\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!57!!11!!7!!3!!2!!0!!1!!0!!67!!14\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[KF Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Sk\u00ebnderbeu Kor\u00e7\u00eb]] (loan)\n|[[2010\u201311 Albanian Superliga|2010\u201311]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Albanian Superliga]]\n|4||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[KF Tirana|Tirana]] (loan)\n|[[2011\u201312 Albanian Superliga|2011\u201312]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Albanian Superliga]]\n|13||2||9||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||5\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Incheon United FC|Incheon United]] (loan)\n|[[2012 K-League|2012]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[K-League]]\n|6||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u